We are interested in three land use metrics: percent pervious surface in watershed, percent vegetated surface in watershed, and percent tree cover in wetland. I use the sqldf package to gather and calculate these (other packages would work but I am most used to SQL language as a GIS user)

INDEPENDENT VARIABLES SiteName= the name of the river the sample was taken from plus a 1 2 or 3 indicating the downstream to upstream-most position Restored= whether or not the site had undergone RSC engineering by Underwood Habitat= qualitative measurement of what might attract macros to the area R: Cobble riffle V: Aquatic vegetation (living) U: Shaded undercut bank L: Dead layers of leaf litter Size= Square meterage of the watershed, measured from downstream-most site FlowRate= Cubic centimeters per second of water moving through a carefully-chosen transect of the given river DO= Dissolved oxygen measured in miligrams per liter by YSI sampler Temperature= Temperature of water in degrees Celsius measured by YSI sampler Conductivity= Conductivity of water in S/cm measured by YSI sampler PblCount= Average of the three longest pebble axes, taken for 25 pebbles at each site (modified Wolman pebble count) PerviousPct= % of river’s watershed that is covered in a pervious surface (forest cover, cropland, etc) VegPct= % of river’s watershed that is actively covered in vegetation TreePct= % of river’s watershed that is wooded Date= day of year sample was taken

DEPENDENT VARIABLES MacroTally= Raw number of macroinvertebrates at each site TotalMass= Sum of mass (in mg) of all macroinvertebrates at sampling site EPTAsPct= The % of the total number of macroinvertebrates that were Ephemeroptera (mayflies), Plecoptera (stoneflies), or Trichoptera (caddisflies). These three orders are of special importance because they are highly disturbance-sensitive. NumTaxa= Number of distinct taxa at a sampling site ShannonDiversity= Site’s Shannon Diversity Index value, a good metric that factors in both species richness and species evenness NumFFG= Number of distinct functional feeding groups (shredder, scraper, gatherer, predator, filterer) represented in a sampling site’s biota FFGDiversity= The Shannon Diversity Index but run on FFG instead of taxa

##PART TWO ANSWERING THE QUESTIONS ~ STATISTICAL TESTS Question 1- Are restored stream-wetland complexes supporting a higher biomass and functional feeding group diversity of macroinvertebrates than unrestored streams? Independent variable: Restored Dependent variable: TotalMass, EPTAsPct, NumFFG, FFGDiversity (Qualitative vs. Quantitative- best to use Kruskal-Wallis to test and bar graphs to display)
